msgid "AWaRe Access"
msgstr ""

msgid "AWaRe A"
msgstr ""

msgid "Access antibiotics that have a narrow spectrum of activity and a good safety profile in terms of side-effects."
msgstr ""

msgid "AWaRe Watch"
msgstr ""

msgid "AWaRe W"
msgstr ""

msgid "Watch antibiotics that are broader-spectrum antibiotics and are recommended as first-choice options for patients with more severe clinical presentations or for infections where the causative pathogens are more likely to be resistant to Access antibiotics."
msgstr ""

msgid "AWaRe Reserve"
msgstr ""

msgid "AWaRe R"
msgstr ""

msgid "Reserve antibiotics that are last-choice antibiotics used to treat multidrug-resistant infections."
msgstr ""

msgid "ATC-5 Groups"
msgstr ""

msgid "AWaRe Groups"
msgstr ""

msgid ""
"AWaRe is the WHO classification of antibiotics introduced by WHO as part of the 2017 Model List of Essential Medicines.\n"
"In the AWaRe classification, there are three categories of antibiotics:\n"
"• Access antibiotics that have a narrow spectrum of activity and a good safety profile in terms of side-effects.\n"
"• Watch antibiotics that are broader-spectrum antibiotics and are recommended as first-choice options for patients with more severe clinical presentations or for infections where the causative pathogens are more likely to be resistant to Access antibiotics.\n"
"• Reserve antibiotics that are last-choice antibiotics used to treat multidrug-resistant infections.\n"
"This classification can be used to give an indirect indication of the appropriateness of antibiotic use. The World Health Organization (WHO) has defined a target that at least 70% of global antibiotic consumption at the national level should be from the Access group."
msgstr ""

